	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Time for another really long post to clear some things up.<BR>
<BR>
At level 20, Clerics are not that powerful. For those of you at this point, you will be enjoying Daring - a decent buff. Holy Might - great stun spell. Healing - it heals! But you simply will not be powerful. DO NOT expect your melee to get better. Pretend you aren't even holding a mace or staff. Better still, throw your weapon in the garbage and hold a Manastone (it looks cool =) For clerics, melee is great up to level 15 or 20. After that, it begins to get pointless. Most mobs have double attack and much better defense and offense skills than you. Use spells.<BR>
<BR>
For those of you complaining, &quot;We don't get this, we don't get that, I want this, I want that&quot; you need to step back and think. EverQuest is a class based game. What this means is we sacrifice one thing in exchange for another. Necromancers sacrifice being well-liked, having any kind of armor or melee skills or any kind of strength or hit points at all in return for being the most powerful offensive class in the game. In contrast, Clerics sacrifice their offensive abilities to be the best defensive players in the game. Sure, as a cleric, it would be great to have invis and teleport and ice comet and duel wield ykeshas. But then you would be a Clerwizzwarric not a Cleric! <BR>
<BR>
Lastly, I feel I need to tell you people how to play this class (lol). There are, indeed, several ways to play a Cleric and several ways NOT to play a cleric. Lets do the positive stuff first:<BR>
1) The group cleric version A. Focuses on wisdom. Heals, buffs and stuns all the time. VERY RARE use of direct damage to finish off attackers.<BR>
2) The group cleric verion B. Has a bit higher AC and melee type skills than Version A and tends to use stuns and direct damage as well as other utility spells. This cleric is NOT the mail healer in the group (ie your grouped with another cleric or druid or shaman or otherwise)but serves as a general purpose member of the group (we can be versatile if we want)<BR>
3) The soloist cleric. This cleric uses heals and buffs on himself mostly, and solos a LOT. A lot of undead, but even though others make it sound tough, we clerics know we can solo just about anything..undead or not. <BR>
<BR>
Don't forget, Clerics are group leaders. They have to make the calls: when to fight, when to run, what to pull, how much to pull. The tanks will be relying on you to make the right call. Once you become a very experienced cleric, you get a very good feel for how the group is doing. I have a mental note of everyone's max and current HP, which buffs are on who, who has how much mana and what mobs with what abilities at what level are we fighting. And most of all, how much mana do :I: have! You people who get bored medding must be doing something wrong. I love medding, if I didn't have to med my head would blow up trying to keep track of everything. My cleric can get off a greater heal with about 1/3 bubble of mana. Supirior heal with about a 1/2 to 2/3 bubble. These two places on my manabar are extremely important to any high level cleric as there is nothing worse than standing up, saying &quot;here comes the heal!&quot; and then seeing &quot;insufficient mana .. your tank is screwed&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The soloist cleric is different. We only really have root, direct damage and stun to use. When soloing Sand Giants, I open with Retribution (level 44 DD), run like mad (jboots) and root. Retribution, Root, Retribution, Root. Eventually the SG will fall (hopefully not on you). Stun is almost useless soloing... in a group it serves to give you time to cast, or give the tanks a break for a second. If a Sand Giant gets so close to me at level 50 than I can't cast, Im probably toast soon anyway! Personally, I find soloing to be fun once and a while (Giants are my personal favorite) but group play to be the most fun, and best XP. <BR>
<BR>
And for any lower level cleric still looking for a good reason to play cleric class... here are some cold hard numbers for you:<BR>
<BR>
Best Cleric spells: (at level 50)<BR>
Level 44. Retribution. 520 damage (240 mana)<BR>
Level 44. Banish Undead. 585 damage (225 mana)<BR>
Level 39. Compelte Heal. Full heal (400 mana)<BR>
Level 34. Supirior Heal. 600 HP (250 mana)<BR>
Level 49. Resurrect. Restore 90% lost XP from death and teleport to corpse. (700 mana)<BR>
Level 49. Sound of Force. 220 damage w/stun<BR>
Level 49. Word of Devine. (Help me on this one, I haven't cast it in a while, I think its 300dmg area of effect but numbers could be off)<BR>
Level 44. Resolution. Buffs +230HP +AC<BR>
Level 44. Symbol of Naltron. +400 HP<BR>
Level 49. Shield of Words. +AC (lots of AC!)<BR>
<BR>
I hope I've wet a few people's appitites enough to stick with this class. Feel free to email me, as always, with questions if you have em!<BR>
<BR>
Salien<BR>
Former Level 50 Cleric<BR>
Bertoxxulous (my server, not my god, lol)<BR>
Tunare (my god, not my server!)
				</font>
			</td>

